<div id="bookReviews">
  




  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_138815464" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/138815464" />
    <a title="Boozy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2017129-boozy"><img alt="Boozy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1313448831p2/2017129.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/138815464?book_show_action=true">Jan 06, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Boozy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Boozy" href="/user/show/2017129-boozy">Boozy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2017129-boozy?shelf=intelligence">intelligence</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2017129-boozy?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer138815464" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18021512859005374371">Well, here goes. <br/><br/>Pros: <br/><br/>The author is a former intelligence professional, regardless of what fans of espionage fiction think, there is absolutely no replacement for having actually worked in the community.<br/><br/>This book does seem to show the various levels of the community, from boots on the ground to policy at the top, where desired end results may not always synch.<br/><br/>It&apos;s partially set in San Francisco, which is a totally kickass city.<br/><br/>The author did partially go into the mindset of a C/O. The majority </span>
  <span id="freeText18021512859005374371" style="display:none">Well, here goes. <br /><br />Pros: <br /><br />The author is a former intelligence professional, regardless of what fans of espionage fiction think, there is absolutely no replacement for having actually worked in the community.<br /><br />This book does seem to show the various levels of the community, from boots on the ground to policy at the top, where desired end results may not always synch.<br /><br />It's partially set in San Francisco, which is a totally kickass city.<br /><br />The author did partially go into the mindset of a C/O. The majority of this type of book I've read, either completely skips this or from the onset makes the protagonist out to be a "rebel" or non-conformist.<br /><br />--------------------------------------------(SPOILER ALERT)-----------------------------------------<br /><br />The good guys don't always get their target. Too often in this genre the success rate of the protagonists are far too high. The fact that there was some failures does add to the reality.<br /><br />BONUS: the portions regarding the Tango were absolutely terrific!<br /><br />----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br /><br />Cons:<br /><br />I felt that too little attention was paid to the interpersonal interactions between the characters, particularly with the Irish character.<br /><br />While i'm not looking for instructions on what intelligence folks call tradecraft, (there are plenty of books out there that do that) i would have liked to see it a bit more fleshed out in the book. <br /><br />While the author seemed to stress the importance of HUMINT relationships i didn't feel that they were well represented here. Not enough detail.<br /><br />Secondary characters weren't well developed, while the interaction between the protagonist and the female love interest are nice, they didn't seem to go anywhere nor was she developed enough to not seem more than a 2D character.<br /><br />------------------------------------------(SPOILER ALERT)-------------------------------------------<br /><br />Facial recognition software as well as that of biometrics has come extremely far in its sophistication, there was little to no mention of it, and it allowed the terrorist characters to freely move about the areas of operation. <br /><br />----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br /><br />Overall, i did like this book. I hope that Mr De Mello continues to write in the genre particularly to continue to develop the characters. While it may not be noticed by some readers of the genre, there are small nuances throughout the book which lend to the authenticity i believe of real world intelligence. I would love to attend a speaking engagement by the author.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18021512859005374371" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

